    rationale: "Linaclotide is a 14-amino-acid synthetic peptide that is a structural analog of endogenous guanylin and uroguanylin. It acts on GC-C (guanylate cyclase-C), a transmembrane receptor-enzyme on the LUMINAL surface of intestinal epithelial cells. SECRETORY MECHANISM: Linaclotide → GC-C activation → intracellular cGMP ↑↑ → PKG-II activation → phosphorylation of CFTR (cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator) chloride channel → Cl⁻ secretion into lumen + HCO3⁻ secretion → sodium and water follow osmotically → increased luminal fluid → softened stool + accelerated intestinal transit. ANALGESIC MECHANISM: cGMP also exits the cell basolaterally → EXTRACELLULAR cGMP in the submucosal space → acts on visceral afferent C-fibers and Aδ-fibers → reduces neuronal excitability (possibly through cyclic nucleotide-gated channels) → decreased visceral hypersensitivity → reduced abdominal pain independent of the laxative effect. This DUAL mechanism (secretory + analgesic through one signaling molecule) is what makes linaclotide uniquely effective for IBS-C (where both constipation AND pain must be addressed). Side effects: diarrhea (most common, dose-related — mechanism-based). Contraindicated in children <2 years (fatal dehydrating diarrhea in juvenile mice).",
